(490, 'https://news.google.com/rss/articles/CBMidmh0dHBzOi8vd3d3LmZvcmJlcy5jb20vc2l0ZXMvYmlsbHJvYmVyc29uLzIwMTkvMTIvMjcvc3BvdHRlZC10ZXNsYS1tb2RlbC15LXByb3RvdHlwZXMtc3RhcnQtcG9wcGluZy11cC1pbi1tb3JlLXBsYWNlcy_SAXpodHRwczovL3d3dy5mb3JiZXMuY29tL3NpdGVzL2JpbGxyb2JlcnNvbi8yMDE5LzEyLzI3L3Nwb3R0ZWQtdGVzbGEtbW9kZWwteS1wcm90b3R5cGVzLXN0YXJ0LXBvcHBpbmctdXAtaW4tbW9yZS1wbGFjZXMvYW1wLw?oc=5&hl=en-IL&gl=IL&ceid=IL:en', 'www.forbes.com', 'Spotted: Tesla Model Y Prototypes Start Popping Up In More Places - Forbes', 'The new Tesla Model Y is seen at its unveiling in Hawthorne, California on March 14, 2019. (Photo by ... [+] Frederic J. BROWN / AFP)        (Photo credit should read FREDERIC J. BROWN/AFP via Getty Images)\nAFP via Getty Images\nAs the big annual odometer teeters on the verge of rolling over to 2020, Tesla ( TSLA ) buyers who put down a $2,500 deposit (of sorts) on the upcoming Model Y crossover earlier in 2019 will likely see the New Year as a milestone towards the arrival of their new electric chariot, and a sighting posted to YouTube on Thursday should help heat up the hype for what could be earlier-than-expected summertime deliveries.\nPosted by popular YouTube denizen StevenMConroy , who has a penchant for drone videos of trains, motorcycle shenanigans and apparently spotting ultra-rare supercars , the thankfully steady-handed Conroy happened upon a glossy white pre-pro Model Y parking nose-out in San Luis Obispo. Conroy caught some great looks as he circled the Tesla, which was sporting some nice touches including a dual-motor badge, fancy new wheels and an apparent “de-chrome” treatment that made the door handles and window trims a touch more low profile. It would probably look a bit sinister in black.\nConroy calls the wheels “Power Sports Aero Wheels” but they are also known as Gemini wheels, a possible upcoming option for the Model 3 Performance, so seeing them on the close cousin Model Y should be no great surprise. Overall, the new Tesla crossover looks good, with typical (for Tesla cars at least) rounding for aerodynamics and expected features like a glass roof and retractable door handles.\nComing off the hype and shock of the Tesla Cybertruck , it’s almost refreshing to see an updated version of a “normal” Tesla that’s headed our way. The Model Y blends the chub nose of the Model 3 with the tall tail of the Model X, and it should seat seven adults (according to Tesla) although the rear two seats might best serve tall children or those that will never need to shop at the Big-N-Tall store. There are no images of the interior, so we can’t tell if this is the 7-seater, which is a $3,000 option over the usual five-place machines.\nMORE FOR YOU\n', 'TSLA', '2019-12-27'),
